\hypertarget{in-the-standard-library}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{In The Standard
Library\protect\hyperlink{in-the-standard-library}{}}{In The Standard Library}}\label{in-the-standard-library}}

We made a fork of libc++. \VERB|\NormalTok{=delete}|ing all the methods
was trivial, except for some methods on \VERB|\NormalTok{string\_view}|
(which are implemented in terms of the \VERB|\NormalTok{=delete}|d
\VERB|\NormalTok{string\_view::substring}|). All test cases (except for
the \VERB|\NormalTok{=delete}|d methods) passed after some rather minor
adjustments (e.g.~replacing
\VERB|\NormalTok{get\textless{}0\textgreater{}(v)}| with
\VERB|\NormalTok{*get\_if\textless{}0\textgreater{}(\&v)}|).

\hypertarget{in-practice}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{In
Practice\protect\hyperlink{in-practice}{}}{In Practice}}\label{in-practice}}

Since we aren't changing the semantics of any of the classes (except
\VERB|\NormalTok{=delete}|ing non-critical methods), it is fair to say
that all of the (implementer \emph{AND} user) experience gathered as
part of Hosted applies the same to Freestanding.

Therefore, the more important question is, does it work? Yes! For
example, the \href{https://www.etlcpp.com/}{Embedded Template Library}
offers direct mappings of the \VERB|\NormalTok{std}| types. Even in
operating systems level libraries, like Serenity's
\href{https://github.com/SerenityOS/serenity/tree/master/AK}{AK} use
these utilities.

